Package com.cohorte.ethernetip.cipconnector

Class IOproperty

java.lang.Object
com.cohorte.ethernetip.cipconnector.IOproperty
public class IOproperty
extends java.lang.Object
T he CIPConnectionPathValidator class that performs syntax validation for cip Path. CIP path can be coposed of strictly 8 hex values otherwise it wouldn't be accepted (validated). This class uses java pattern and matcher to perform the pattern matching validation A matcher requires a path and a pattern, the pattern should be compiled with a regex expression that is created at the object construction phase. The Connection path should match the following regex pattern :

^([01]?\d\d?|2[0-4]\d|25[0-5])\.([01]?\d\d?|2[0-4]\d|25[0-5])\.([01]?\d\d?|2[0-4]\d|25[0-5])\.([01]?\d\d?|2[0-4]\d|25[0-5])$

description

^ Matches the beginning of the string, or the beginning of a line. This matches a position, not a character.
( .... ) Groups multiple tokens together and creates a capture group for extracting a substring or using a backreference.
[ .... ] Match any character in the set.
a - f Range Matches a character in the range "a" to "f" (char code 97 to 102). Case sensitive..
A - F Range Matches a character in the range "A" to "F" (char code 65 to 70). Case sensitive.
0 - 9 Ran Matches a character in the range "0" to "9" (char code 48 to 57). Case sensitive..
{2} Quantifier Match 2 of the preceding token.
\s whitespace Matches any whitespace character (spaces, tabs, line breaks).
* Quantifier Match 0 or more of the preceding token.
{8} Quantifier Match 2 of the preceding token.
$ End Matches the end of the string, or the end of a line.

    • RPI

      private java.lang.Integer RPI
      requested packet interval :
      The requested packet interval shall be the requested time between packets in microseconds. The format of the RPI shall be a 32-bit integer in microseconds. The requested packet interval shall be the time between packets requested by the receiving device. The value shall be used to allocate bandwidth at each of the producing nodes. The allocation of bandwidth may have to be adjusted when the actual packet rate or actual packet interval is returned, since it is possible for the two values to differ. The path time-out value at each of the intermediate and target nodes shall also be set to the connection time-out multiplier times the API. The RPI is therefore required for all connections.

    • realTimeFormat

      private de.re.eeip.cip.datatypes.RealTimeFormat realTimeFormat
      Every connection has a pre-defined Real Time Format, which is the format of the data in the O to T and T to O direction. What Real Time Format shall be used is not specified in the Forward_Open, but in the [Connection Manager] section of the EDS file. Although the Real Time Format is not provided in the Forward_Open frame, it still has influence on the connection sizes within the network connection parameters. The following Real Time Formats are available:

      32-Bit Header Format (includes run/idle notification)

      Modeless Format (no run/idle notification)

      Heartbeat Format

    • trigger

      private TriggerType trigger
      The transport class and trigger specify the type of transport required for the connection. This information shall not be used by the connection manager but passed on to the application. The application shall determine if the transport type is supported and if an instance of the required transport is available. we discussed some details of how to form transport trigger parameters, see cip documentation

    • auto_size_detect

      private boolean auto_size_detect
      when a parameter is set to true, the connection implicit will automatically detect the connection size. in a auto_size_detect connection we send an explicit get to the target to get the T_O and O_T size of data . if you read the cip documentation, you will notice that in an implicit connection we configure a set of parameters, so that both target and originator knows size of data and all information required before open forward a data flow

    • priority

      private de.re.eeip.cip.datatypes.Priority priority

      Scheduled priority

      For scheduled priority, the RPI shall be the packet rate of the repetitive data. On links that support bandwidth allocation, bandwidth shall be reserved for this packet. For scheduled priority, the data shall also be restricted to the specified packet rate, which means that if data arrives at an intermediate node faster than the specified packet rate, the node shall filter the packets to the specified rate. Since each node’s scheduled priority update rate is in discrete quanta, the Actual Packet Interval (API) may be smaller (more rapid) than the RPI. The path time-out value shall be set to the Connection Time-out multiplier times the API.

      High priority

      For high priority, the RPI shall be used to set the path time-out in the intermediate and target nodes. The RPI shall therefore be set to the slowest packet rate expected, which shall preclude having the connection close due to a path time-out. The longer the path time-out, the longer the time required to reclaim resources in the intermediate nodes as a result of faults in the network. Since the high priority is not quantsed at any of the nodes, the API shall equal the RPI. To maintain consistency, however, the time-out value shall again be set to the Connection Time- out multiplier times the API.

      Low priority

      For low priority, the RPI shall be used to set the path time-out in the intermediate and target nodes. The RPI shall therefore be set to the slowest packet rate expected, which shall preclude having the connection close due to a path time-out. The longer the path time-out, the longer the time required to reclaim resources in the intermediate nodes as a result of faults in the network. Since the low priority is not quantised at any of the nodes, the API shall equal the RPI. To maintain consistency, however, the time-out value shall again be set to the Connection Time-out multiplier times the API.

    • ownerRedundant

      private boolean ownerRedundant

      Redundant EtherNet/IP Implicit IO Scanner

      When the originator establish a connection, he cannot connect to the same target simultaneously unless the owerRedundant is set to true. the same thing for the target.
      notice: it's not allowed to set ownerRedundant to true for both target and originator at the same time
